      <h2>The Mechanics of a Short Squeeze</h2>
      <p>A short squeeze is a market phenomenon that occurs when a heavily shorted asset experiences a rapid increase in price. Short sellers borrow shares and sell them, hoping to buy them back later at a lower price. However, if the price starts to rise unexpectedly, these short sellers begin to accrue losses.</p>
      <p>To cut their losses or meet margin calls, short sellers are forced to buy the stock back to return the borrowed shares. This aggressive buying pressure drives the stock price even higher, forcing more short sellers to cover, creating a cascading feedback loop of upward price momentum.</p>

      <h3>Key Ingredients for a Squeeze</h3>
      <ul>
        <li style="margin-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong style="color: var(--text-main);">High Short Interest:</strong> Typically, a stock needs a short interest of at least 20% of its tradable float to have enough "fuel" for a squeeze.</li>
        <li style="margin-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong style="color: var(--text-main);">High Days to Cover:</strong> A ratio above 5 indicates that it would take over five days of normal trading volume for shorts to fully exit. The longer it takes, the harder the squeeze.</li>
        <li style="margin-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong style="color: var(--text-main);">An Unexpected Catalyst:</strong> Positive earnings surprises, new product announcements, buyouts, or simply massive retail buying pressure (as seen in the meme stock era) can trigger the initial spike.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Historical Examples -->
