      <h3>GameStop (GME) — January 2021</h3>
      <p>The most famous short squeeze in modern history. GameStop had a short interest exceeding 140% of its float—meaning more shares were shorted than actually existed. A massive influx of retail buying, coordinated on social media, combined with a gamma squeeze from options trading, sent the stock from under $5 to over $120 (split-adjusted) in weeks.</p>
      <h3>AMC Entertainment (AMC) — June 2021</h3>
      <p>Following in GME's footsteps, the struggling theater chain had over 20% short interest. Supported by retail enthusiasm and a reopening economy catalyst, AMC squeezed from $2 to over $70, severely punishing institutional short sellers.</p>
      <h3>Clover Health (CLOV) — June 2021</h3>
      <p>During the retail trading frenzy of mid-2021, Clover Health became a major target for the Reddit crowd. With high short interest and retail traders looking for the "next GME," CLOV experienced a massive influx of volume, causing the stock to squeeze from around $9 to over $28 in just a few days.</p>
